Background

		Mr. Ashok N. Bakhru served as the President of ABN Associates since November 1998. Based on the foregoing, Mr. Bakhru is experienced with financial and investment matters. Mr. Bakhru served as the President at ABN Associates from July 1994 to March 1996. He served as the Chief Administrative Officer, Chief Financial Officer and Executive Vice President of Finance & Administration of Coty Inc., from April 1996 to November 1998. He served as the Chief Financial Officer ... and Senior Vice President of Kimberly-Clark Tissue Company (also called as Scott Paper Company). He has been the Chairman at Goldman Sachs BDC, Inc (formerly Goldman Sachs Liberty Harbor Capital, LLC) since March 2013. He served as the Chairman of Lenders Service Inc. from 2000 to 2003. He serves as a Director of Institute for Higher Education Policy. He serves as the Chairman of the Board of Trustees of 77 funds in the Goldman Sachs Fund Complex. He has been an Independent Manager of Goldman Sachs Hedge Fund Partners Registered Fund Llc since June 9, 2004. Mr. Bakhru has been a Director of Equity-Limited Investors II since November 1998. He serves as a Director/Member of the Board of Governors of Investment Company Institute. He has been a Member of Administrative Board of Cornell University since 2006. Mr. Bakhru served as a Director of Arkwright Mutual Insurance Company from 1984 to 1999. He served as a Director of Coty Inc. from April 1996 to November 1998. He served as an Independent Director at Apollo Investment Corporation since October 16, 2008 until June 7, 2013. Mr. Bakhru served as a Director\Trustee of Institute for Higher Education Policy from 2003 to 2008. Mr. Bakhru served as a Member of Administrative Board of Cornell University from 1992 to 2004. He is a Director of the Governing Council of the Independent Directors Council and Mutual Fund Director’s Forum. He has been a Trustee or Director of the Walnut Street Theater since 2006. He is a Member of the Advisory Board of BoardIQ. He was a Trustee of International House of Philadelphia from 1989 to 2004, Walnut Street Theater from 1992 to 2004 and Scholarship America from 1998 to 2005.Read Full Background




